row is located oh the northwest corner of\n18th and iNewton Sts. N. W.\nThat most refined and exclusive section immediately west of\nMt. Pleasant, surrounded bv ONLY high-class homes, rang\ning in cost from $7,000 to $30,000.\nTHEIR CONSTRUCTION IS IDEALLY FIRST CLASS.\nDESCRIPTION Ten large, stylish rooms; FULL\nTILED BATH; approved HOT-WATER heating system;\nfine lawns; southern exposure; FRONT AND BACK\nSTAIRWAYS; servants' room and toilet; stationary laun\ndrv tubs.\nAERAN'GKMEN'T?Parlor, reception hall, dining room, pantry and\nkite en on first floor; THREE I-ARGE BEDROOMS and fully ap\npointed bath on second floor: TWO EXTRA LARGE FIXE SLEEP\n1XG CHAMBERS OX THIRD FLOOR.\nSplendid Valine at $7,150.\nModest Cash Payment, Balance Payable on Easy Terms.\nTO INSPECT?Take F street cars to 17th and Park Road. Mt. Pleas\nant: thence 1 block west and 1 block north. Or telephone Main 487\nor 488, and let us convey you to the houses. Our automobiles and\nsurreys at your disposal.\nWillige, Gibbs Daniel,\n603-05 13th St. N.W.\n\ni\ns\n\n\nBargain*\nHandsome colonial residence,\ncontaining 12 rooms. 2 baths,\nhot water heat, finished in hard\nwood throughout. Lot 20xi:i0 to\nulley. Worth J11,000.\nSpecial Price, J0.300.\nD sirable house, containing\n10 rooms. 2 l aths, hot wai bp\nat. Lot 18x120 to alley. Worth\n$8,750.\nSpecial Price. J8.000\nLight brick and white etona\nfront house, 9 rooms and bath.\nAll mod. imp. Lot 18x85. Sold\nat JS,5uu.\nSpecial Price, J6.750.\nand\n>ites\nB.&O. Freight Station.\nnn?.\nWo H. WALKER, I\n729 BStlhi NoW.\npr?'*V !'T\nn\nrf\nNECESSITIES OF THE NAVY\nHOME MANUFACTURERS CAN\nNOT SUPPLY DEMAND.\nAdmiral Mason Wants Authority to\nBuy Abroad?Guns Out of Date.\nExperimenting With Powder.\nN'aval necessities are such that the do\nmestic manufacturers are unable to sup\nply within a reasonable time ordnance,\nprojectiles, powder and torpedoes for the\nnavy, and Rear Admiral Mason, chi-.-f of\nthe bureau of ordnance, in his annual re\nport, strongly urges legislation that will\nauthorize the department to purchase\nsuch material abroad when \"it is to the\nmanifest interest of the United States.\"\nHp says that the torpedo situation is such\nthat 1UO of these weapons should be\nbought abroad while American manufac\nturers are completing their present con\ntracts and the government factory is be\ning put in running order. There is also\nurgent necessity, he says, for going\njatroad to obtain armor-piercing projec\ntiles and range finders, which American\nmanufacturers are unable to produce.\nGuns Out of Date.\nAdmiral Mason finds it ne^-ssary to re\nplace all the present eight and twelve\ninch guns by others of a later and\nstronger design to admit of the uso of\nsmokeless instead of brown powder. An\nappropriation is asked for withdrawing\nthese old guns and strengthening them\nwith hoops at the muzzle, which is a\nweak point in the present gun.\nIncreased rapidity of fire has rendered\nunsatisfactory tne present methods of\nhandling ammunition In the turrets, and\nIt is considered necessary to replace the\nammunition hoists on all of the older\ntype of battleships.\nSteady progress has been made In the\ndevelopment of a naval powder, but ev -n\nthe best is not indefinitely stable, though\ncareful tests have removed the danger of\ndefective powder escaping detection. A\nprocess has been developed for reworking\nold and suspected powder so as to make\nit as good as new. at about one-quarter of\noriginal cost. Admiral Mason expresses\nthe oflnion that the department is in no\ndanger of toeing oppressed by the powder\ntrust and says he has effected a system\nfor regulating the price to be paid to the\nprivate manufacturer for powder on the\nbasis of the cost of production at the\ngovernment powder works_ at Indian\nHead. A considerable lncrea'se of the ca\npacity of that government plant Is con\ntemplated.\nTo Provide for Bases.\nAdmiral Mason makes a strong plea for\nan appropriation to defray the cost of\nmanufacturing and assembling at two\npoints, one on the Atlantic and the other\non the Pacific, a supply of guns, ammuni\ntion and such material as may be needed\nby the navy to rapidly fortify strategic\npoints that may be seized In time of war,\nas advance bases of operations against an\nenemy, pointing to the lessons of the\nSpanish war and t)he successful opera\ntions of the Japanese as proof of the wis\ndom of establishing such depots.\nAn Item of $'>00,000 is included In the\nestimates for experimental work, and Ad\nmiral Mason points out the necessity of\ninquiry into the chemistry of powder, the\nbest means of preventing the erosion of\nguns, the improvement in shape of the\nprojectiles and finally the testing of the\nresisting power of armor plate by actual\nfiring at long range with heavy guns at\nthick plate. At present penetrations of\nf>hot under such conditions are purely mat\nters of theory.\nNews of Falls Church.\nSpecial Correspondence of The Star.\nFALLS CHURCH. Va.,\nNovember 23, lSW.\nMr. F. N. Dudley has purchased\nthrough Mr. M. E. Church two acres of\nland of Rev. B. W. Pond-on Jefferson\nstreet, and will erect a residence in the\nnear future.\nUnion Thanksgiving services will be held\nnext Thursday morning In tho M. E.\nChurch South. Rev. W. S. O. Thomas,\npastor of the- Baptist Church, will preach\nthe sermon.\nMr. George W. Hawxhurst, who was\nelected Justice of the peace for Falls\nChurch magisterial district at the recent\nelection, has qualified before Judge\nThornton for a term of four years.\nMr. F. E. Parker has commenced the\nerection of a residence on his lot at Great\nFalls Church.\nMr. George W. Maben, his, ?n the peti\ntion of a number of freeholders, been\nappointed game warden for Falls Church\ndistrict by Judge Thornton.\nMr. H. C. Ryer has purchased an acre\nof land at East Falls Church of Dr. J. B.\nGould.\nMiss Mary W. Banks of Atlanta, Ga.,\nwho has been visiting her uncle. Mr.\nG. N. Lester, has returned to her home\nMr. and Mrs. William Quirk of Ash\nburn, Va., are visiting relatives here.\nRev. J. E. Amos, pastor of the M. E.\nChurch, is conducting revival services.\nPresiding Elder Rev. J. W. R. Sumwalt\npreached Wednesday night.\nThanksgiving services will be held by\nthe Presbyterian Sabbath school Sunday\nmorning.\nMrs. Noble Moore will spend the winter\nat Norwood, Ohio.\nBUSINESS tOOKS BETTER\nRAILROAD PRESIDENTS EX\nPRESS HOPEFUL VIEWS.\nTransportation Getting Back to\nNormal Lines and General\nProspect Good.\n4\nNEW YORK, November 23.-Several\nrailroad presidents who have just returned\nto this city from the west expressed hope\nful views of the business outlook In the\nwest, while admitting that tho disturb\nances through which the country is pass\ning must of necessity be reflected in a\nfalling off in railroad earnings.\nB. F. Yoakum, chairman of the exec\nutive committee of the Rock Island and\nFrisco systems, said that business in the\nwest was being resumed and thit business\nmen in the states he visited were main\ntaining a hopeful attitude. Mr. Yoakum\nsaid:\n\"Business is being gradually resumed.\nThe. time for talking about conditions\nseems to have already passed in tihe west\nand they are now looking for a resump\ntion of business on normal lines. X think\nfrom my observations of business condi\ntions in the west that the outlook, all\nthings considered, is satisfactory.\"\nFrank Trumbull, presid-nt of the Color\nado Southern, said that he was hopeful re\ngarding the conditions on his line. Tho\nrecent financial upheaval must, he said,\nhave its effects on all parts of the coun\ntry. but the thought that the Colorado and\nSouthern lines would suffer as little as\nany road in the country. The returns for\nthe second week in November showed In\ncreases of 11 per cent in the gross earn\nings, and so far. he said, business on these\nlines was keeping up will.\nROCKVILLE AND VICINITY.\nMayor Garrett's Plan for Getting\nRehearing on Glen Echo Case.\nSpecial Correspondence of The Star.\nROCKVILLF, Md? November 23, 1907.\nMayor John A. Garrett of Glen Echo\nexpressed himself as confident that thera\nwill be no difficulty about having -tho\nUnited States Supreme Court pass upon\nthe questions recently decided by Judge\nHenderson in the circuit court here In\nconnection with the Conduit road cases.\nHe says he has received the best of\nlegal advice to that effect. He says he\nrecognizes the fact that no appeal from\nthe action of the circuit court can be\ntaken, but declares there is another way\nto have the questions passed upon by a\nhigher court.\nMayor Garrett states that it is pronosed\nto use the recent refusal of Col. Cosby\nof the War Department to permit the\ntown of Glen Echo to make crossings\nconnecting certain streets of the town\nwith the Conduit road, the idea being to\ninstitute mandamus or mandatory in\njunction proceedings in the Suprem\nCourt of the District of Columbia, and\nthat the constitutional questions Involved\nwould carry the1 matter to the Supreme\nCourt of the United StateB.\nMr. Garrett says he do-^s not knew\nwhat the town council of Gl- n Echo will\ndo In regard to the fines col.ected from\nautomobllists. He declares if it Is de\ncided to return them there is am;ile\nmoney in the town treasury for the pur\npose. He has received a communication\nfrom Leckie, Fulton Cox, who repre\nsent a numher of the automobilists, ask\ning what it Is proposed to do in the\nmatt r, but as yet the letter is un\nanswered.\nWilliam T. Walling and Miss Lucy\nDonna Shelton. both of Washington, vis\nited Rockville Thursday and were mar\nried by Rev. S. R. White of the Baptist\nChurch.\nGeorge Andrew Keogh and Mis??\nElva Mabel Kendrick. young Washing\ntonians, Thursday afternoon procured a\nlicense to marry. In making applica\ntion the young man inquired for what\nlength of time the license was good, ex\nplaining' that he wanted it for Decem\nber 16. He was informed that it was\ngood \"until used.\" The youn? coup'e.\nhowever, hastened uptown presumably\nin search of a minister, but whether\nthey got married could not be learned.\nOther licenses to marry, have been is\nsued to the following: Herbert L Of\nfutt and Elizabeth Carter. Richard A.\nParker and Beriha Gertrude Drepen,\nHerbert Thomas and Ollia E. Matthews,\nail of this county.\nMiss Mary L. Withers of Chevy Chase,\nthis county, and Harry C. Kleinschmidt\nof Washington were married at Chevy\nChase last evening by Rev. Alfred Hard\ning. rector of St. Paul's Parish, Wash\nington.\nGeorge Duffln. colored, was Thursday\nsentenced by Judge Henderson in the\ncircuit court at this place to five years\nIn the Maryland penitentiary for an as\nsault upon, with intent to kill, Fiancis\nS. Kilgour, one of the best-known farm\ners of Potomac district.\nThe county commissioners for Mont\ngomery county have appointed the fol\nlowing as trustees of th\" county alms\nhouse: H. B. Gardner. Charles J. Lyd\ndane, Eleazar Ray, M. Wilson Offutt and\nHarry Riggs.\nWilliam K. Jones, a farmer residing\nnear Glen, this county, had two tins\nsteers shot and killed 1-y some one ba\nlieved to have been actuated from spit\nThe county commissioners have offered\na reward of $.\">0 for information leading\nto the apprehension and conviction of\nthe guilty one.\nIS\nHomes in\nINCLESIDE,\n1831-41 Monroe Street.\ni$15,000 Value for $8,000[\nThese superb homes are absolutely be\nX yond criticism and are really incom-\nI parable. They combine all the essential 5>\nI if features which ko to make up the com- \"V\nr& plete home, beinsr HIGH-class in every\nparticular but the TRICE, which is POSI-\nTIVELY LOW for a house of this char-\nacter.\nDESCRIPTION.\nFull three-story mottled brick, with\nbrownstone trimmings. containing eleven\n(11) beautiful and splendidly arranged\nrooms, with two very large baths: panel\nmirrors: double back porches; front and\nback stairways: unique and costly gas\nfixtures; oak mantels; select papering ?nd Jv\nV artistic decorations; 